Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the interest rate on the money market. At its discretion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB aims to keep inflation below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a difficult position: inflation must be "reciprocated" in order to rule out the need for action at a later stage.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Increased food and energy prices were responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybean also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also considerable inflation in 2007 for edible oil and dairy products.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3% inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup orts government crisis
After a long stagnant period, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown significantly until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has had the largest base camp, while the support for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low point of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
In the case of party-like voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one fifth (20 percent) support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are under the parliamentary entry hurdle: they reach two percent in the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who consider the country's economic situation to be "probably bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it to be "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, the families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population anticipates a further deterioration in the situation; only one-tenth is expected to improve.
A Gallup survey conducted in December revealed that 71% of respondents - a historical high - considered the Prime Minister's work "rather bad than right".
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the percentage of supporters for Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust of the leader of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that discontent with the Prime Minister could be managed without a change of government.
After the riots last October, 35% were still in favour of keeping the government and the head of government, this proportion is now only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent replied that they would "certainly" participate, and another 20% would "probably" cast their vote.
By comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go "with certainty" to the polls, another 15% would consider their participation "probably". In view of these tendencies, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
Moved to the group of "with certainty" participants in the referendum, the percentage of opponents of study, practice and hospital fees would be as high as 81, 84, and 89 percent respectively.
Even the most expensive, Tesco increases by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörser trading area have also maintained this year's average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Article from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörser trade triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket of the "Napi" increased by 16 percent this year, but price increases of over 1,000 HUF were recorded in all hypermarkets.
After the prices in the food markets were "galoped off" last December, the inflation rate was not dramatic in percentage terms, compared to the already high, earlier starting level.
However, it has a deterrent effect on consumers that what they paid well below HUF 9,000 last year is not even available for HUF 10,000 this year.
The price of the "Napi" shopping cart exceeded the magical 10,000-HUF limit by at least 91 HUF in the examined markets.
The highest price was 10,573 HUF.
(The price was 6,800 HUF in 6800.)
The prices for unicum and live fish remained almost at the previous year's level, while prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but at Auchan there were 1kg of bread wakes for 139 forints.
There was no competitive fall in the price of the product to below 200 forints.
Also surprising here was the price of a two litre Coca-Cola deposit bottle of less than 200 Forint, so the drink including deposit cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, this year, in the "Napi" shopping cart comparison, Auchan performed the most expensive, and Cora the most favorable.
Our calculations have shown that Cora has increased the prices in the "Napi" shopping cart by 15 percent compared to the Christmas prices last year, while Tesco and Auchan have each increased by 18 percent.
The difference between the cheapest shopping cart of the previous year and the most expensive one of today's year was 12%, while the increase between the cheapest shopping cart of the previous year and the most expensive one of the current year was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1,480.00.
The average price increase in the previous year was 1,206,00 Forint, but the increase in value added tax was noticeable in the prices at last Christmas.
It is precisely this process that has hit trade badly: apparently, department stores were not able to quite decide which price range they should apply to the individual articles, as the effects of the price increase on consumer behaviour were incalculable.
(If the trader is planning the circulation speed of a product poorly, it can fall for substantial profits in the price range, which depends on the traffic intensity.)
Due to Mehwertsteuer, the increase in the "Napi" basket last year was so radical that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 Forint, whereas the price difference with the cheapest basket was only 844 Forint.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forint more than in the previous year, and even the cheapest, there was a price increase of 1,284.00 forint.
Compared to the last two Christmas seasons, the price of daily consumer goods in the hypermarkets has risen by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily confirm the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Office found more than 30 percent inflation over the 12-month period.
For example, in addition to flour, also in eggs.)
However, if you take a look at the "Napi" shopping cart, this seems almost impossible for the latter, as the price level of the product that was already expensive in the previous year has risen by barely more than 10 percent, even in the worst case.
Obviously, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers - after all, they were able to shift the drastic price increase to the multinationals.
In the golden trade triangle the hypermarkets do not complain; it is constantly reported of good years.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores are no longer looking at prices.
Large quantities of food are purchased, and durable food goes over the counters in pallets.
Wednesday morning, there were endless snakes in all three department stores at the cash desk when the number of customers suddenly exploded.
However, the country reports a lower customer frequency, so many multinationals complain to opinion researchers that they could not even achieve the planned sales, not only for food, but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overburdening of personnel - all factors that are not particularly conducive to containment of infections, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed due to the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December of this year, 1094 infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were certainly registered in hospitals, but the number of cases is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, almond inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are given too high or misused improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotics-resistant, which spread rapidly in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with a weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in older or low-body weight patients, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday life in the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA there is only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the mitigation of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, the hospitals should examine the admitted patients and immediately isolate MRSA infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the Epidemiology Centre.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and disease patterns in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the agent, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rarer among the outpatients or patients in primary care.
The disinfectants are saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to the other by the nursing staff.
It is precisely for this reason that hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the local hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds narrowly lined up, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less well-paid hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that actually favour the development of infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, such infections are demonstrably far less common, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
According to first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
