EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three credit agreements in Budapest on Friday totalling EUR 400 million, to be used in education, transport and environmental infrastructure and the energy sector.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement of EUR 100 million was previously signed and the current agreement concerns the use of the EUR 200 million granted.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement will also be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has granted a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary and the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be channelled into research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the U-Bahn line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of the metro financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan rates are EURIBOR-linked and the loan is made available by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, free of commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is looking attentively at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who is still buying in the EU's cheapest market, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is no doubt the most sought-after pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and seaside homes.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will also attract investors sooner or later, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the very favorable area of Russe has more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfers' paradises, and thus attract tourists in addition to the summer and winter season also in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also seek to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski resorts are predominantly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or run down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of businessmen who invest in order to increase value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is constantly becoming more expensive, as a result of ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are lowest in Bulgaria, but there has been an annual increase of 21 percent in the last five years.
The rise in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue at the conference is whether developed countries are prepared to provide both financial and technological support to developing countries in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on assistance to developing countries was also reached.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member council, expected to be at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary’s Six Percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that by 2020 the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (measured according to 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "after-2012 agreement" is being successfully achieved. The Union would even be willing to commit to a 30 percent reduction, provided that other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to do their best and responsibly to meet their commitments.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the states that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed itself to a minus of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee of the UN in its recent report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and increasing the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
Initially, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations conducted against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The footage filmed with helmet-mounted miniature cameras is controlled at the air base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are put on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, as well as the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
According to defence expert Gordon Mackenzie, propaganda published in this way is almost free of charge compared to conventional television advertisements, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, since they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored recordings, also make it into the net - such as those showing the death of the soldiers: The somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films talk about the losses at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, many of the war sites in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been loaded onto the platform, but only recently did the British discover this "genus" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a somewhat different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-scattered simulation.
