More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions are forming their coordination committee on Friday for the indefinite duration of the strike starting on Monday.
On Saturday a large protest assembly is held, on Monday - on the day of the referendum to the Health Insurance Act - the work stoppage begins.
Strike-related, significant traffic obstructions are expected, as rail traffic is almost completely discontinued, and Budapest's public transport companies (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of the strike on Monday will be announced jointly by the League of Trade Unions and the Trade Union Federation on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee is also established, which is responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A large-scale protest assembly is held on Saturday, and as of Monday, all the organizations that have joined the strike lay down the work indefinitely unless agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike beginning on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act was not defined.
If the National Council does not accept the Health Insurance Act, the unions immediately withdraw the call for strike.
If the law is passed, however, the strike committees meet to discuss the further action.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that the vote on the Health Insurance Act will take place only in the late evening hours, or even at midnight.
The strikes, which begin on Monday, will have to be expected to have considerable traffic obstructions: the railway workers lay down their work for an indefinite period, the majority of public transport and more than half of Volán's companies stop in the morning.
