Festive days are not everywhere Holidays
In Hungary, public holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redistributing the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year gives us less such days.
In the EU and America, too, something else is understood as "feiertag".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and work-free days.
Working days are mostly church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year celebrations can rest.
All year round we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15, which commemorates the 1848 revolution, and October 23, the 1956 revolution memorial day.
On 20 August the foundation of the state, on 1 May the work is celebrated, on 1 and 2 November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday postponement" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be worked out in the end, is for long years determined by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants alike.
Only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays, are excluded.
This year, the work regulations are only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country will be stopped formally, as most take time compensation for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the vacation specifically cancelled for this purpose.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or the end of the week, so that there will be less redistributions on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second re-disposition is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to work on Friday, October 24th in advance.
The end of the year, however, will be completely marked by the holidays, after everything will lie and stop from December 24th, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six daunting little things to annoy colleagues
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we don't notice any more: they bring "color" into everyday life at the workplace.
The only question is whether you get used to these minor inconveniences, or if you better face the challenge and try to avoid them deliberately, for others annoying situations.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called" - says a colleague.
That they missed a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by calling the marketing department and confessing with regret that you would have forgotten to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the matter is dismissed with an apology.
Before engaging in embarrassing excuses, you should consider how to prepare truly unpleasant moments for your colleagues and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it's not there.
Yesterday the notebook was still on the desk - this morning it is gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague's desk?
Without asking, you should not borrow anything from colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has come away.
So, no envelopes or post-it from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more there, if you need it urgently.
Talking about colleagues' private lives?
There is no effective means of stopping a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what to who?
Where and why?
One should not tie the information (or conjecture) about the private life of the colleagues to everyone's nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and reveals his innermost secret to us, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to keep silent like a grave, rather than directing the one who is not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Reported sick for no reason?
If you call the office to report sick when you call on painful headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable right now, or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, unsuspendable accomplishments, projects with fixed appointments must now be done by colleagues instead of yourself.
So don't mess with colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you won't make it to the office the next day, or that something could come in between, which is why you have to stay home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Summing, giggling, calling
Is the work being deepened, but is it suddenly disrupted by the loud giggle of the colleagues?
Inadvertently listening to a telephone conversation you shouldn't have heard?
One should not bother colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which one leads over their heads), trampling, constant scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not precisely in a task (write, plan, organize).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not finished on time, one has to send an important letter or important messages forgotten, one should not look for the fault of one's own forgetfulness with others!
If possible, do not talk about the chaos in the office or the noisy colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake or make up for the missing is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training Pants and Slaps: Comfortable for home, but has nothing to lose in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress accordingly in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
To make it all right - or how to become uninteresting for others
Stop and go traffic, the car in the middle of every morning traffic jam.
A strange melody sounds from the radio: the sound of a violin, coupled with electronic effects.
I'm turning the volume up.
The tempo changes, to the previous sounds comes the bass, and as a real sound jewel a female choir.
