"Szezon" by Ferenc Török).
The formation, which had initially appeared in smaller clubs, only became known to the wider audience when the magazine "wan2" ranked their first album from 2002 among the top 50 domestic albums and Zagar, together with Yonderboi, voted almost the only trendsetter, also marketable in the West.
No doubt Zagar and his band were "trendy", but nobody was interested in whether they like to wear this brand.
The band reacted as it should: with a new, even better album.
The new album, titled "Cannot Walk Fly Instead", could open up new avenues for them, but the title already expresses the desire for continuity with the Pécs years.
The expression comes from the time when Baláz's Zságer was still traveling with another band.
The airy, flying allusion would also be fine, but besides the ethereal character of the music, the louder guitar, the influences of rock'n'roll - corresponding to the zeitgeist and the trends - stand out.
With these songs, singer György Ligeti, who lives in England and works with the band "The Puzzle", introduced himself at the premiere at the Millenáris.
A song from the album has even made it to the radio hit - the mr2 Petőfi, which has been broadcasting pop music from early to late, has gradually put the earworm on the listener with the number "Wings of Love", which was recorded with the participation of six local singers ("Underground Divas").
So everything's fine (?).
The hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit raises the question: To what extent is your music reserved for a certain layer?
Balázs Zságer: The term "shift music" doesn't mean much to me.
In my opinion, there are two boxes in pop music, not mainstream and underground, or alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
Even the so-called alternative or underground music can be shallow and meaningless, but they can also only be produced for sale, which makes it commercial music.
Also a good pop number can arise from an honest motif.
The listener's willingness to accept also works according to this principle, independent of languages and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of the Hungarian and foreign audiences to your music?
B. Zs.: Abroad, especially west of us, pop music has a greater tradition.
Not only teenagers or Twens go on concerts, but also the older audience.
They follow the trends in pop music that are happening around them much more attentively, because they also consider them to be a part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What role does the audience play in your work?
Is it important who, where, how many listen to your music?
B. Zs.: Of course it is a good feeling to see that more and more are coming to our concerts.
But we never composed for the market.
With us the music does not arise to serve a purpose, but for a certain reason.
The role of the audience is usually noticeable at the concerts, where there is already a mutual interaction, but that, in turn, only exists in the incomprehensible changes of the moment.
Nevertheless, I have noticed that if you want to make it right for everyone, you are no longer interesting.
hvg.hu: How far do you want to follow Yonderboi's example?
He is on the road as a soloist and has built his career more in the West.
B. Zs.: We don't really go his way, not to mention that you always try to interpret this into our music.
We see ourselves as more of a team player who trusts in the musical presence of the other and lets them unfold.
At first, of course, comparisons of our work with Yonderboi's were inevitable, as several of us came out of his band and took a different path.
hvg.hu: In the charts of mr2 Petőfi, "Wings of Love" comes first.
Many have only heard the name Zagar in connection with this number.
Was the opening deliberately staged with a slightly more popular style towards a wider audience?
B. Zs.: We had no plans to write a hit, which is then supposed to be a drawhorse for the album.
This song is about more.
It was intended as the finale of the album, with which we wanted to dissolve the sound orgy and the more difficult topics.
hvg.hu: How did you select the six singers?
Why them, what was the guiding principle?
B. Zs.: The basic idea was to make a gospel-like choir.
Then came the idea to assemble the choir from talented soloists of the domestic music scene.
This is how the six-member choir was created - Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikő Hodosi [Neo], Juci Németh - which we then apately baptized "Underground Divas".
hvg.hu: Did you want the song to be the same, or did the girls help shape it?
B. Zs.: The number has been in the instrumental version for a long time, but when the material for the album was finished, we thought that this number still "needs something".
The chord sequence has formally demanded a vocal voice.
I sang the melody the same night, later they learned the girls.
It all came practically at once and horribly spontaneous.
I remember, I was quite electrified at the time, but it was already necessary for the "Divas".
With my voice alone, the song would never have become so strong.
hvg.hu: On the record as well as at the concert you had the impression that the girls were in the background.
There is no solo part (apart from the short solo by Judy Jay), they have no role of their own, sing together completely and are not louder than the music, so their singing is not only accompanied by the music.
They also stood on stage in the back.
Is it on purpose?
B.Zs.: That they stood in the back was because of purely technical problems.
However, we deliberately didn't want to give them solo roles.
The number is also about forgetting a little bit about your ego, forgetting who came from and where to go, we simply allow these particular wings, the wings of love, to lift us up.
I would like others to feel this euphoric state that we felt when the song came into being.
hvg.hu: Which was the most elaborate song?
B. Zs.: None at all in musical creative work, there have been more difficult tasks in mixing.
For example, in "Dorian Gray's Dilemma", in which I play on a concert piano, or in "Rock'n'Roll Goes To The Girls", where the groove did not want to work longer, but gradually everything joined together, like a puzzle.
hvg.hu: What's your favorite number from the new album?
B. Zs.: This is constantly changing with the concerts and also now that I have "let go" the album.
Currently it is "Prophet Is A Fool", "Escape From The Earth" and the number "Never The Same".
