This is a more appreciative issue for the media, and that is why they pay more attention to it.
An argument among politicians is much more interesting to the public than sober figures.
The state budgets suffered from three weaknesses in the past social democratic governments, which the 2008 budget cannot eliminate at once:
The first is the high proportion of expenditure that is legally binding, not only pensions, but also social expenditure that the "silent" coalition of ČSSD and KSČM (Communists) decided on last year before the elections.
The second is budgetary deficits as a result of the first weakness.
The third limitation is the public finances deficit, i.e. local government budget deficits.
However, the biggest risk is not the government budget deficit.
This budget is public and reasonably under control.
But a true time bomb is the budget deficit of the municipalities.
Many mayors spent more than income from taxes, taxes, and bank loans on opening up sources of investment, often ill-considered debt securities, through which they over-indebted their councillors.
In recent years, they have managed to pay off this debt by mass selling of shares in the energy and other utility networks they had received from the state in the wake of privatisation.
