Banks want to cope with crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis on the financial markets.
Thus, more than $100 billion of auctions will reach the currency markets by means of auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend money to each other.
For example, the US Fed is sending $40 billion at auction, another 24 making it loose for the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time, following the attacks of 11 September, that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to ward off or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote in a report for its customers Bernard Baumohl of the consulting company Economic Outlook Group.
"Coordinated central bank action has reduced the likelihood of recession in the US from 65% to about 50%," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion because of unserved loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further billions of losses.
"The central banks must have been really afraid of what else can happen when they decided to do so," said the chief economist of ABN Amro, Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into recession, possibly with an impact on economic growth around the world.
The central banks have chosen to reduce the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used in the money lending between banks, after having failed to do so.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid of lending each other money, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further reduction in interest rates," said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting of the Reuters agency.
Some analysts believe that this move by central banks is contributing to the heating up of the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the case of the real estate market in the US.
