On Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province at the last negotiating meeting in Vienna.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo have ended Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, a sixth and final discussion session without being able to overcome their controversy about the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties could not reach an agreement on the status, said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace is at stake in the region, its American counterpart, Frank Wilsner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to honour their commitments to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, suggesting that there are clear tensions.
End of placements on 10 December
Troika mediators, which unite the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ishinger, Wilsner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks at Baden, near Vienna, formed the sixth and final meeting of negotiations since the Troika received the mandate for a new mediation from the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked Kosovo's independence from the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this end date.
Russia was and remains advocate of a negotiated solution, a friendly solution, said Botsane-Khartchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
Kosovo has been under the administration of the UN for eight years, and the Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is willing to announce them unilaterally if the Security Council should not decide in their favor.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Regrettably no agreement could be reached, the President of Kosovo's autonomous authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where these negotiations of last chance have been conducted since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province shared his regrets.
However, he added that the plan proposed by Belgrade included autonomy from a past that led to murders and deportations.
Domino effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, felt that a compromise should always be sought and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence from the province.
Belgrade believes that it particularly favours a "domino effect" in a region that is so weakened by the Revolutionary Wars of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision be taken solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally holds a veto right.
Kosovo Parliament will have the last word
Only a decision from the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia, said Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
The journalists were told by Fatmir Sejdiu that Kosovo's parliament would have the last word on status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence from the Albanian-speaking population would proceed in consultation with the Western countries.
