Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmates' lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen still process tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
