In addition to modernising financial markets, MIFID, which redefines the Investment Services Regulation, is pursuing an improvement in investor protection, increasing the control claim of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive enables both specialised firms and natural or legal persons to provide financial advice and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS), the consulting companies that are affiliated with investment and brokerage companies of securities.
It also expands the number of financial transaction execution systems, adding to regulated circulation markets the multilateral securities trading systems and the internationalisation of trading orders, which would eventually compete with current economic operators.
The law obliges investment companies to communicate the priorities of their company profile, the confrontation and forms of dealing with risks on the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the control task of the CNMV.
