The climate on Venus could reveal a glimpse of the future of the Earth
Venus was perhaps once a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spaceship on orbit shows that the planet resembles a distant twin of the Earth even more than was previously aware.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbour to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have had conditions that would have been very similar to those on earth and could have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unchecked carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rotational speed, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the Venus Express spacecraft of the European Space Agency, which has been studying the planet for one year, provide a sobering view of how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford, one of the heads of the Venus Express Mission, said, "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that of Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data makes it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment."
