Labour Party Pain
Gordon Brown has discovered another pit to fall in; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No noble titles seem to have been sold, no politician's Paris hotel bills paid, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the discovery that a rich businessman has veiled donations for the British ruling Labour Party over more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something without which the competitive Gordon Brown would have done well.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister withdrew from the demand for an election, in a stupid way insulting the British intelligence by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced this decision, there was hope that it would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly discerning Liberal Democrat representative, put it, the once feared Brown of Stalin has evolved into Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a battered bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Badly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have raised corporate associations against the government.
The tax loss of 25 million people's personal data showed unimaginable administrative messes.
A trio of retired generals started an insurrection in the Upper House in protest against cuts in military spending: to be ministers of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the many donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's Secretary General (and their former Head of Performance) has already resigned.
None of this means Brown is irrevocably breaking off.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it impossible to govern.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their scepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a Prime Minister will improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there for long, this delay is over: the public service is beginning to leak; cabinet ministers are starting to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to deny Tony Blair, he was his senior lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are related to decisions taken by Brown as Chancellor of the Treasury Department.
And even if it wasn't directly involved in Blair's mishap - like the long "money for nobility" investigation of political party funding - voters may assume it was him.
Nevertheless, Brown's situation is not as bad as it looks
The mistakes are not as terrible as the Conservatives describe them.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely swindled.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new fuss about political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be the case, but he was not entitled to make the decision.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear and exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement, but not that it's illegal, will of course have to ask some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's main financial collector, who was told about the weird donations in October.
But so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing that indicates that he knew of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He has quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered down this determination by grasping for a known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to make the measure full, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons to be learned are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the Independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a sweeping reform of political party funding.
This would require the Labour hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to abandon the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a partymate such as Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partial facts.
Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve a victory is through incontestable righteousness and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is America’s credit crisis affecting the credit card market?
When blood is in the water, it is only natural that dorsal fins swirl around excitedly.
Now that America's real estate market is hurting, the predators are targeting the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs predict that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both derecognition and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are not recoverable or more than 30 days late.
The HSBC announced last month that it took a $1.4 billion fee collection from its American consumer financing, partly due to the weakness of credit card buyers.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and delays are still low.
According to Moody, the 3rd quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in US private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt case of bankruptcy applications, which in turn accounted for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of applications (and hence default fees) would rise again, whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate or not.
Industry also reports solid payment rates showing how much of its debt consumers pay off every month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the standstill in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, anticipates that the output for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
Direct infection channels between the property credit crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: it is more likely that consumers will take credit card debts, now that home loans dry out.
However, card issuers look at the flow of money instead of capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be beneficial for the card issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates fall when real estate is less valuable than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also react much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a quick revaluation of assets.
"We won't wake up one day and reassess the loans completely," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's Chief Financial Officer.
Even if a sudden undercovering crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are considerably more real.
If lower house prices and credit cutbacks push America into recession, industry will undoubtedly face a grimer future.
Keep looking for these shark fins.
